{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Problem\n`rebar explain plan` / `explain review` (and `explain <criterion-id>`) read their guide\nmarkdown from `config.repo_root(...)/docs/...`. `repo_root` resolves to the *consuming\nproject's* git toplevel (or cwd), never the rebar install. So when rebar is installed as a\nlibrary/CLI/MCP and run against another project, the `docs/` tree is absent and every\n`explain` guide lookup fails with missing-file. A client hit exactly this (\"the author guide\nlives in the rebar source repo, not this project\").\n\n## Goal\nMake the plan-authoring guide (writing-a-passing-plan.md) and code-authoring guide\n(passing-code-review.md) accessible through rebar's CLI, MCP, and Python library surfaces from\nany installation, matching the established OSS convention for runtime-needed data files:\nthe canonical copy lives *inside* the import package, read via `importlib.resources` (the same\npattern rebar already uses for `criteria_routing.json`).\n\n## Approach\n1. Move the two prose guides to `src/rebar/_guides/writing-a-passing-plan.md` and\n   `src/rebar/_guides/passing-code-review.md` (canonical, in-package) and add\n   `src/rebar/_guides/__init__.py`. Hatchling ships all files under `src/rebar`, so they land\n   in the wheel automatically.\n2. Change `AUTHOR_GUIDES` from `dict[str, tuple[str, ...]]` (path components under `docs/`) to\n   `dict[str, str]` mapping guide name -> bare filename, e.g.\n   `{\"plan\": \"writing-a-passing-plan.md\", \"review\": \"passing-code-review.md\"}`.\n   `explain_guide(name)` resolves via `resources.files(\"rebar._guides\") / AUTHOR_GUIDES[name]`\n   and drops the `repo_root_path` parameter (resolution is repo-root independent). Unknown name\n   still raises `ExplainError(\"unknown-id\", ...)`; a genuinely absent packaged resource raises\n   `ExplainError(\"missing-file\", ...)`.\n3. `explain_criterion(id)` renders the section directly from the packaged registry via the\n   existing `_guide_section_body(criterion)` (the same content `regenerate_criteria_guide`\n   builds the doc from) instead of reading `docs/plan-review-criteria-guide.md`. Overlay\n   project criteria still resolve via `load_criteria(repo_root=repo_root_path)`; unknown-id and\n   malformed-registry states are preserved; the repo-root missing-file state is removed.\n4. Leave `docs/writing-a-passing-plan.md` and `docs/passing-code-review.md` as thin pointer\n   files to the in-package canonical source so existing links (docs/README.md, AGENTS.md)\n   resolve.\n5. Keep the dev/CI machinery unchanged: `regenerate_criteria_guide`, `validate_criteria_guide`,\n   `_guide_path`, and the Pass-4 coach deep-links to the docs anchor.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] With `REBAR_ROOT` set to a directory containing no `docs/`, `rebar explain plan`,\n      `rebar explain review`, and `rebar explain <criterion-id>` (e.g. F1) each exit 0 and print\n      the guide/section (installability guarantee).\n- [ ] The library calls `registry.explain_guide(\"plan\"|\"review\")` and\n      `registry.explain_criterion(\"F1\", repo_root_path=<dir-without-docs>)` return the content\n      without raising (no dependency on repo-root `docs/`).\n- [ ] The MCP `explain_criterion` tool returns `{criterion_id, section}` for a guide name and a\n      criterion id under the same repo-root-independent condition.\n- [ ] Both guides are present as packaged resources: `resources.files(\"rebar._guides\")` contains\n      `writing-a-passing-plan.md` and `passing-code-review.md`.\n- [ ] `docs/writing-a-passing-plan.md` and `docs/passing-code-review.md` still exist as pointer\n      files (existing links do not 404).\n- [ ] `make lint` and `make typecheck` pass; `tests/unit/test_plan_review_explain.py` passes,\n      updated to assert repo-root independence instead of the old \"missing-file when the repo\n      has no docs\" behavior, plus a test that both guides are packaged."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784746821919526001,"uuid":"8e382f36-2bd0-4698-9c31-ac0f34d2451c"}